`Multiply` returns a `double` so you can just add the results together:

    var total = Multiply(2.5, 2) + Multiply(6, 7);
    Console.WriteLine($&quot;result: {total}&quot;);

Multiply should only be responsible for multiplying numbers, if you try to return result of summation of multiplied values it&#39;s a sign of **Single Responsibilty** violation. So you can do one of the followings:

    double value1 = Multiply(2.5, 2);
    double value2 = Multiply(6, 7);

    double total = value1 + value2; // which is equal to 47 in your case

Or pass results of multiplied values to a sum method as below:

    static double Sum(double d1, double d2)
    {
        return d1 + d2;
    }

and call it like this:

    var total = Sum(value1, value2);

Or you can simple do it like this:

    var total =  Multiply(2.5, 2) + Multiply(6, 7);

there are many ways to do it but you can capture the results the Multiply

    using System;
    using System.Collections.Generic;
    using System.Linq;
    using System.Text.RegularExpressions;
    
    namespace Rextester
    {
        public class Program
        {
        
        public static double result = 0;
        
        static double Multiply(double firstParam, double secondParam)
        {
            return result += firstParam * secondParam;
        }
        
        public static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Multiply(2.5, 2);
            Multiply(6, 7);
            Console.WriteLine(result);
        }
    }
    }

